Dev Build Cleanup Checklist (Post-Stabilization)

1. Lock the Toolchain (No Accidental Versions)

Goal: Same inputs → same build, everywhere.

Node version pinned

.nvmrc (or .node-version) exists and matches:

devcontainer

CI

Dockerfile

Package manager pinned

packageManager field in package.json (e.g. pnpm@9.x)

Corepack enabled

corepack enable documented or enforced

No implicit language installs

Devcontainer / Dockerfile does not install Go, Python, Java, etc. unless required

Fail fast on version mismatch

Preflight script errors if Node / pnpm versions differ

2. Dependency Hygiene

Goal: Deterministic installs, minimal surface area.

Single lockfile

Exactly one of: pnpm-lock.yaml / package-lock.json / yarn.lock

Lockfile committed and respected

CI fails if lockfile changes unexpectedly

No floating versions

No "\*" / ^0.x on critical deps

Remove unused deps

Run pnpm prune or depcheck

Explicit overrides

Use pnpm.overrides for known bad transitive deps

Audit path exists

pnpm audit (or equivalent) documented

3. Devcontainer / Docker Sanity

Goal: Rebuildable, minimal, boring.

Correct workspace root

Container opens at repo root (not one directory up/down)

No missing scripts

All onCreateCommand / postCreateCommand files exist

No optional scripts executed by default

Guard with || true only where justified

BuildKit explicitly enabled

DOCKER_BUILDKIT=1

No cached state dependency

Full rebuild works after docker system prune -af

Named volumes documented

Clear what is safe to delete

4. Environment Variables & Config

Goal: Predictable config, no leaks.

.env.example is complete

Every required var documented

No secrets in repo

Scan for API keys, tokens, certs

Environment layering is explicit

.env.local, .env.ci, .env.docker behavior documented

Fail on missing env

App errors early if required vars missing

Config drift eliminated

One source of truth (no duplicated env loaders)

5. Build & Startup Path

Goal: One way to start the system.

Single canonical dev command

e.g. pnpm run dev or ./dev up

No “magic” side effects

Dev command does not mutate repo unexpectedly

Cold start verified

Works after deleting:

node_modules

.vite

.next

build cache dirs

Port ownership clear

No silent port collisions

Explicit readiness checks

Services wait for dependencies properly

6. Type Safety & Linting

Goal: Errors caught before runtime.

Typecheck is separate

pnpm run typecheck exists

No ignored TS errors

No @ts-ignore without explanation

Strict mode on

strict: true unless justified

Lint rules enforced

CI fails on lint errors

Consistent formatting

Prettier or equivalent, no debate

7. Tests: Minimal but Meaningful

Goal: Catch breakage, not inflate metrics.

Smoke test exists

App boots, main route loads

Security regression tests

SSRF, CSRF, auth boundaries

Critical path coverage

One test per core workflow

Tests deterministic

No reliance on time, network, randomness

Fast test suite

Dev tests < 10–15s

8. Logging & Debuggability

Goal: Failures explain themselves.

Startup logs

Clear “what is running where”

Error messages actionable

Not just stack traces

No noisy logs

Debug logs gated behind flags

Sensitive data redacted

URLs, headers, tokens sanitized

9. CI Alignment

Goal: CI ≈ local.

CI uses same Node/pnpm versions

CI runs the same commands

typecheck → lint → test → build

No CI-only hacks

Fast failure

Typecheck runs before build

Artifacts reproducible

Same commit → same output

10. Repo Hygiene

Goal: New contributors don’t get lost.

README is accurate

No stale instructions

One setup path

“Do this, not three alternatives”

Scripts are named clearly

dx:_, dev:_, build:\*

Dead files removed

Old Dockerfiles, scripts, configs

TODOs triaged

Security / infra TODOs tracked, not forgotten

Final “Stability Seal” Test

Before declaring the dev build clean:

Fresh machine / new container

Clone repo

Run one command

App runs

Tests pass

Rebuild works after full cache purge

If that passes, your dev environment is stable, repeatable, and boring — which is exactly what you want.
